#: ../../../index.rst:203
msgid "Detailed docs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:3
msgid "Sphinxcontrib-rust"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:5
msgid ""
"This is a `Sphinx`_ extension for integrating Rust programming language "
"projects in Sphinx builds. It will work with existing Rust docstrings with "
"some minor tweaks. See :doc:`docs/compatibility` for writing docstrings "
"compatible with both rustdoc and this extension. See :doc:`docs/limitations` "
"for known limitations compared to rustdoc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:9
msgid ""
"You can also read this documentation on `Gitlab Pages`_ or `readthedocs`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:19
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:21
msgid ""
"This is primarily meant for teams and projects that are already using Sphinx "
"as a documentation build tool, and would like to include documentation for "
"Rust projects in it along with Python, C, and other languages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:24
msgid "Using the extension adds the following functionality:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:26
msgid ""
"Rust specific :doc:`directives <docs/directives>` and :doc:`roles <docs/"
"roles>` that can be used to define and link to Rust items."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:28
msgid "rustdoc comments may be written in reStructuredText."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:29
msgid ""
"Various Sphinx features and extensions can be used to generate and publish "
"the docs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:31
msgid ""
"This is not a replacement for `rustdoc`_, and since rustdoc is a part of the "
"Rust language itself, it will not have all the same features as `rustdoc`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:34
msgid ""
"The goal is to provide a way for teams and projects using multiple languages "
"to publish a single, consolidated documentation and use this, along with "
"rustdoc, as part of the documentation workflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:37
msgid ""
"See :doc:`docs/limitations` for some cases where the tool will not work the "
"same as rustdoc and :doc:`docs/compatibility` for any tweaks required to "
"make the tool work with existing docstrings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:43
msgid "Installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:45
msgid "There are two components that are required for this to work"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:47
msgid "The ``sphinx-rustdocgen`` Rust crate for extracting the docs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:48
msgid "The ``sphinxcontrib_rust`` Python package, which is a Sphinx extension."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:50
msgid "Both components are installed when installing the Python package with"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:52
msgid "pip install sphinxcontrib-rust"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:56
msgid ""
"The installation will check for ``cargo`` in the ``$PATH`` environment "
"variable and will use that to build and install the Rust executable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:59
msgid ""
"The executable is built with the Rust code shipped with the Python package "
"to ensure that the Rust executable and Python package are always compatible "
"with each other."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:62
msgid ""
"Make sure that the directory where ``cargo`` installs the executable is in "
"``$PATH`` as well. If the default installation directory is not part of the "
"``$PATH`` environment, the installed executable may be specified in the "
"Sphinx configuration with ``rust_rustdocgen`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:66
msgid ""
"If for any reason the crate does not get installed with Python package, it "
"can be installed directly from crates.io with ``cargo install sphinx-"
"rustdocgen``. Make sure to install the same version of the create as the "
"Python package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:70
msgid "Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:75
msgid "rustdoc compatible Markdown docstrings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:77
msgid ""
"This is most probably what you want to do and allows generating Sphinx "
"documentation separately from rustdoc output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:79
msgid ""
"To use the extension along with rustdoc, add the extension to Sphinx's "
"``conf.py`` file and also add the `myst-parser`_ extension. Sphinx also "
"needs to be `configured for Markdown builds`_. Use the code snippet below "
"with your crates specified in ``rust_crates`` to enable all if this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:83
msgid ""
"Using various extensions for myst-parser, existing docstrings can be "
"rendered with Sphinx with minimal changes. See :doc:`docs/compatibility` for "
"details on how to write docstrings that can work with both rustdoc and "
"Sphinx."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:86
msgid ""
"extensions = [\"sphinxcontrib_rust\", \"myst_parser\"]\n"
"source_suffix = {\n"
"    \".rst\": \"restructuredtext\",\n"
"    \".md\": \"markdown\",\n"
"    \".txt\": \"markdown\", # Optional\n"
"}\n"
"# See docs/compatibility for details on these extensions.\n"
"myst_enable_extensions = {\n"
"    \"attrs_block\",\n"
"    \"colon_fence\",\n"
"    \"html_admonition\",\n"
"    \"replacements\",\n"
"    \"smartquotes\",\n"
"    \"strikethrough\",\n"
"    \"tasklist\",\n"
"}\n"
"rust_crates = {\n"
"    \"my_crate\": \".\",\n"
"    \"my_crate_derive\": \"my-crate-derive\",\n"
"}\n"
"rust_doc_dir = \"docs/crates/\"\n"
"rust_rustdoc_fmt = \"md\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:111
msgid ""
"This will generate the documentation from your Rust crates and put them in "
"the ``docs/crates/<crate_name>`` directories. :doc:`docs/including` "
"describes the various ways to integrate the documentation in the Sphinx "
"build. The Rust items can then be referenced using :doc:`docs/roles` from "
"other docs in the Sphinx build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:115
msgid ""
"See the `configuration options for MyST`_  for other options that are "
"supported by myst-parser. They can be changed as required to customize the "
"generated docs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:119
msgid "reStructuredText docstrings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:121
msgid ""
"Using the extension, it is also possible to write the Rust docstrings in "
"reStructuredText. Note that this makes the docstrings unusable with Rustdoc "
"and should only be considered when the rustdoc documentation will not be "
"used. Publishing a crate with such docstrings is still possible, but the "
"documentation on docs.rs for the crate will not be rendered properly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:126
msgid ""
"To enable RST docstrings, add the extension to the ``conf.py`` file and "
"configure it appropriately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:128
msgid ""
"extensions = [\"sphinxcontrib_rust\"]\n"
"rust_crates = {\n"
"    \"my_crate\": \".\",\n"
"    \"my_crate_derive\": \"my-crate-derive\",\n"
"}\n"
"rust_doc_dir = \"docs/crates/\"\n"
"rust_rustdoc_fmt = \"rst\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:138
msgid ""
"This will generate the documentation from your Rust crates and put them in "
"the ``docs/crates/<crate_name>`` directories. You can link against the "
"documentation in your ``toctree`` by specifying the path to ``lib`` file and "
"any executables. See :doc:`docs/including` for more details. The Rust items "
"can then be referenced using :doc:`docs/roles` from other docs in the Sphinx "
"build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:144
msgid "Recommendations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:146
msgid ""
"Use a HTML theme that allows expanding the TOC in the sidebar completely. "
"For example, if using ``sphinx_rtd_theme``, set the ``navigation_depth`` in "
"``html_theme_options`` to -1 in the ``conf.py`` file (``html_theme_options = "
"{\"navigation_depth\": -1}``). This makes the sidebar much better to use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:149
msgid ""
"It is possible to write docstrings in Markdown and other documentation in "
"reStructuredText. The configuration should be the same as what is described "
"in :ref:`md usage`. The roles and directives will work the same regardless "
"of the choice of the docstrings syntax."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:154
msgid "Options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:156
msgid ""
"Options are simply Python variables set in the ``conf.py`` file. Most "
"options can be provided as a global value or a dict of values per crate, "
"with the crate name as the key. The options that are global only are listed "
"separately below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:0
msgid "rust_crates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:159
msgid ""
"(Required) A dict of crate names and their source code directories. This "
"must be a dict even for a single crate. It determines which crates are "
"documented. The directory should be the one which contains the ``Cargo."
"toml`` file for the crate and each crate in the workspace must be listed "
"explicitly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:0
msgid "rust_doc_dir"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:164
msgid ""
"(Required) A directory under which to write the docs for all crates, or a "
"dict of directory for each crate name. The directories will be read by "
"Sphinx during the build, so they must be part of the source tree and not "
"under the build directory. The build process will create a directory with "
"the crate name under this, even when specified per crate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:0
msgid "rust_rustdoc_fmt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:170
msgid "Either ``rst`` or ``md``. (Default: ``rst``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:0
msgid "rust_visibility"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:171
msgid ""
"Only includes documentation and indexes for items with visibility greater "
"than or equal to the setting. The value can be ``pub``, ``crate`` or "
"``pvt``. Visibility restrictions like ``super`` and ``in <path>`` are not "
"supported currently and are treated as private. (Default: ``pub``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:0
msgid "rust_strip_src"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:174
msgid ""
"Whether to remove the ``src/`` directory when creating output files or not. "
"The default is ``True``, since that was the initial behavior. So, instead of "
"creating output files as ``<crate_name>/src/<mod_name>.rst``, the output "
"files are created as ``<crate_name>/<mod_name>.rst``, effectively removing "
"``src/`` from the paths. Set to ``False`` for crates that use a different "
"path. (Default: True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:181
msgid ""
"The below options are global options, and cannot be specified per crate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:0
msgid "rust_generate_mode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:183
msgid ""
"One of ``always``, ``skip`` or ``changed``. If set to ``always``, all "
"documents are regenerated. If set to ``skip``, the docs are not regenerated "
"at all. If set to ``changed``, only docs whose source files have been "
"modified since they were last modified are regenerated. (Default: "
"``changed``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:0
msgid "rust_rustdocgen"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../index.rst:188
msgid ""
"The path to the ``sphinx-rustdocgen`` executable to use. The path must be an "
"absolute path or relative to Sphinx's working directory. (Default: Obtained "
"from the ``$PATH`` environment variable.)"
msgstr ""
